        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1964-06-03T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1964-06-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="221"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d221">
                <head>221. Memorandum From the Department of State Executive Secretary (<persName
                        corresp="#p_RBH1" type="from">Read</persName>) to the President’s Special
                    Assistant for National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_BMG2" type="to"
                        >Bundy</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d221fn1">Source: Johnson
                        Library, National Security File, Subject File, Trade—General, Vol. I [1 of
                        2], Box 47. Limited Official Use.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1964-06-03">June 3, 1964</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Extra-Long Staple Cotton</item>
                </list>
                <p>This memorandum is for Messrs. Dungan, Feldman, and <persName corresp="#p_BFM1"
                        >Bator</persName>.</p>
                <p>My memorandum to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BMG2">Buddy</persName> dated May 12,
                    1964 transmitted a copy of a letter to Under Secretary of Agriculture <persName
                        corresp="#p_MCS1">Murphy</persName> setting forth the Department’s
                    objections to a proposed export subsidy on extra-long staple cotton.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d221fn2">See <ref target="#d220fn3">footnote 3, Document 220</ref>.
                            <persName corresp="#p_RBH1">Read</persName>’s May 12 memorandum to
                            <persName corresp="#p_BMG2">Buddy</persName> is in the Johnson Library,
                        National Security File, Subject File, Trade—General, Vol. I [1 of 2], Box
                        47.</note> Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MCS1">Murphy</persName> has commented
                    upon that letter in a memorandum to the White House dated May 27, 1964.<note
                        n="3" xml:id="d221fn3">
                        <ref target="#d220">Document 220</ref>.</note> Our comments on Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_MCS1">Murphy</persName>’s memorandum are forwarded herewith.</p>
                <p>The points we wish to stress are these: (1) under present circumstances we cannot
                    grant an export subsidy consistently with our obligations under the <gloss
                        target="#t_GATT1">GATT</gloss>; (2) the benefits to be derived from such a
                    subsidy, which would affect only one percent of our total cotton production, are
                    nowhere near commensurate with the damage that would be done to our relations
                    with the major producers of extra-long staple cotton and with the developing
                    countries generally; and (3) the present surplus results from a substantial
                    increase in the acreage allotment since 1960–61 due to overestimating the
                    anticipated consumption increase. This is a problem which can and should be
                    corrected domestically, rather than exported to the disruption of the world
                    market.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">J.J. deMartino</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="4" xml:id="d221fn4">
                            <persName>De Martino</persName> signed for <persName corresp="#p_RBH1"
                                >Read</persName> above <persName corresp="#p_RBH1">Read</persName>’s
                            typed signature.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
